- GENERAL PRINCIPLES
Clarity/Readability: Code easy to understand, maintain.
Simplicity (KISS): Prefer simple solutions; avoid over-complexity.
Meaningful Names: Variables, functions, classes clearly reveal purpose. Avoid abbreviations.
SRP: Components (functions, classes, modules) do one specific thing. Keep small, focused.
DRY: Don't Repeat Yourself. Extract to reusable units. Single source of truth.
Modularity: Break complex problems into smaller, manageable units.
Named Constants: Use for magic values (no magic numbers). Define at top of script or in dedicated constants autoload/script. Use const for immutable values.
Logical Structure: Group related code. Use consistent, logical naming for files/folders.
Encapsulation: Hide implementation details; expose minimal, clear interfaces.
Avoid Side Effects: Functions should primarily compute and return values, minimizing changes to external state unless explicitly intended (e.g., node property setters, signal emissions).

- GDScript NAMING CONVENTIONS (Godot 4)
Classes & Nodes: PascalCase (e.g., PlayerController, ScoreLabel). Use class_name for global registration.
Functions & Methods: snake_case (e.g., calculate_damage, _process_input).
Variables & Properties: snake_case (e.g., move_speed, current_health).
Constants: UPPER_SNAKE_CASE (e.g., const MAX_SPEED = 100.0, const DEFAULT_GRAVITY = Vector2.DOWN * 980).
Signals (custom): snake_case (e.g., health_updated, enemy_defeated).
Private (by convention): Prefix with underscore: _my_private_var, _my_private_func().
Booleans: Prefixes like is_, has_, can_ (e.g., is_jumping, has_permission).

- GDScript FORMATTING & SYNTAX
Indentation: Use Tabs.
Type Hints:
Variables: MANDATORY.
Prefer inferred type var speed := 10.0 when the type is obvious from the right-hand side.
Use explicit type var data: Dictionary = load_complex_data() when the type is not immediately obvious or for clarity.
var health: int = 100
var target_node: Node2D
Functions: MANDATORY for all parameters and return types.
func calculate_speed(distance: float, time: float) -> float:
Local Variables: Prefer local variables. Avoid global variables unless essential (e.g., Autoloads).

- GDScript FUNCTION & CONTROL FLOW
Early Exits (Guard Clauses): MANDATORY. Handle edge cases, errors, and preconditions at the beginning of functions to reduce nesting and simplify logic.
## Calculates the area of a rectangle.
## Returns 0.0 if width or height is non-positive.
func calculate_area(width: float, height: float) -> float:
    # Guard clause for invalid input
    if width <= 0.0 or height <= 0.0:
        push_warning("Attempted to calculate area with non-positive dimensions.")
        return 0.0
    return width * height

Avoid if-else where possible: Prefer guard clauses for early exits. Ternary operators (value_if_true if condition else value_if_false) can be used for simple assignments if they enhance readability, but guard clauses are generally clearer for control flow.
Conciseness: Keep functions short and focused on a single responsibility.
Async: Use await with signals or create_timer for async operations.
await get_tree().create_timer(1.0).timeout
await some_node.custom_signal_name

- GDScript COMMENTING & DOCUMENTATION
Public API Documentation: Use ## (double hash) for all public (exported or globally accessible) functions, variables, signals, and classes/scripts.
Script/Class: ## Brief description of what this script/class does. (At the top of the file).
Function:
## Brief one-sentence summary of the function's purpose.
## Optional: More detailed explanation if complex logic.
## Parameters:
## - param_name: Purpose of this parameter. (GDScript type hints cover the type itself).
## Returns: Description of what is returned. (Use "Nothing." or omit if void and obvious).
func my_complex_func(value: int, label: String = "default") -> String:
    # ... function logic ...
    return "result based on " + label + " and " + str(value)

Variables/Signals: ## Description of the variable/signal's purpose.
## Emitted when the player's score changes.
signal score_updated(new_score: int)

Internal Comments: Use # (single hash) for all other comments (inline, private logic explanations). Explain why, not what if code is self-evident.
GDScript ERROR HANDLING
Explicit Checks: Check return values from functions that might fail (e.g., load, get_node, file operations).
assert(condition, "Error message if assert fails"): Use for development checks to catch logic errors early; document if critical.
push_error("Descriptive error message"), push_warning("Descriptive warning"): Report issues to Godot's debugger.
Custom Error Signals: For recoverable errors that other game systems might need to react to.
Return Error Codes/Null: Functions may return specific error values (e.g., an enum or null) on failure; document this behavior clearly in docstrings.

- GODOT 4 SPECIFIC GUIDELINES
class_name: Use for custom types/nodes for global script class access & editor integration.
class_name PlayerStateMachine, "res://path/to/optional_icon.svg"
Node References (@onready, NodePaths):
Use @onready var node_ref: Type = get_node("Path/To/Node") to reliably get node references.
Avoid get_node() calls in _process or _physics_process; cache references.
Prefer unique node names (%UniqueNodeName) or scene-unique paths for get_node robustness.
Signals:

Heavily prefer signals for decoupling.
Define custom signals clearly with typed arguments: signal score_changed(new_score: int)
Connect signals via editor or code: some_node.connect("signal_name", Callable(self, "_on_signal_name")).
Lifecycle Methods (_init, _ready, _process, _physics_process, _notification):
Keep concise. Offload heavy logic to other functions or use call_deferred.
_physics_process strictly for physics-related updates. _process for non-physics frame updates.
@export: Use extensively for Inspector-configurable variables. Provide type hints.
Organize exports with @export_category("Category Name"), @export_group("Group Name").
Resources: Use custom Resource scripts. preload() for compile-time, load() for runtime.
Input Handling: Use Godot's Input Map. Check inputs using Input.is_action_pressed(), Input.get_vector(), etc.
Scene Instancing: Prefer instancing scenes (.tscn) over creating complex node hierarchies purely in code.
File Structure: Maintain logical project folder organization (e.g., scenes/, scripts/, assets/).
Autoloads (Singletons): Use sparingly for truly global systems.
StringName: For performance-critical string lookups.
match Statement: Use for complex conditional logic if it improves clarity over many if/elif/else.
Godot Style: Adhere to official Godot documentation & community style guides.

- GENERAL CODE QUALITY & MAINTENANCE
Continuous Refactoring: Regularly improve code structure, readability, and performance.
Technical Debt: Identify and address technical debt proactively.
Boy Scout Rule: Leave the code cleaner than you found it.

- GENERAL TESTING
Testable Code: Write code facilitating testing (small functions, clear inputs/outputs).
Unit Tests: For core logic, algorithms. Consider Godot Unit Test (GUT) or similar.
Coverage: Test edge cases, error conditions, typical usage.

GENERAL VERSION CONTROL (e.g., Git)
Commit Messages: Clear, concise, descriptive (why & what).
Commit Scope: Small, focused commits (single logical change).
Branch Names: Meaningful, descriptive.

AI WORKFLOW & CODE VALIDATION
Context: Godot Engine (v4.x) using GDScript.
AI Goal: Generate GDScript that is correct, adheres to these rules, and likely passes gdformat and aligns with best practices without manual developer intervention.
Instruction for AI (Post-Modification Expectation):
Anticipate Developer Actions: Developer will likely run gdformat . and other validation. Code review against these guidelines is expected.
Your Responsibility:

Do NOT execute gdformat or other commands.

Generate code proactively meeting these standards.

If unsure, err on side of official Godot style and common GDScript best practices for clean, readable, idiomatic code.
